y_of_the_wild/ ''Cry of the Wild''] by [[Bill Mason]]\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q18498}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wolf, Gray}}\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1758|Gray Wolf]]\n[[Category:Arctic land animals]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Carnivorans of Asia]]\n[[Category:Carnivorans of Europe]]\n[[Category:Carnivorans of North America]]\n[[Category:Extant Middle Pleistocene first appearances]]\n[[Category:Fauna of Siberia]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Rocky Mountains]]\n[[Category:Holarctic fauna]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Asia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Europe]]\n[[Category:Mammals of North America]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the Arctic]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the Middle East]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene carnivorans]]\n[[Category:Scavengers]]\n[[Category:Wolves|Gray Wolf]]\n", "name_user": "2600:8800:6900:ab5:ccd7:d3cf:6d64:bae0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolf"}
{"title_page": "Charles Wyndham, 2nd Earl of Egremont", "text_new": "{{Other people|Charles Wyndham}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name               = The Earl of Egremont\n|honorific-suffix   = [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]]\n|image              = Charles Wyndham, 2nd Earl of Egremont by William Hoare lowres color.jpg\n|imagesize          = 240px\n|alt                = \n|caption            = \n|order              = \n|office             = [[Secretary of State for the Southern Department]]\n|term_start         =  9 October 1761\n|term_end           = 21 August 1763\n|monarch            = [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]]\n|primeminister      = [[John Stuart, 3rd Earl of Bute|The Earl of Bute]]<br/>[[George Grenville]]\n|predecessor        = [[William Pitt, 1st Earl of Chatham|William Pitt]]\n|successor          = [[George Montagu-Dunk, 2nd Earl of Halifax|The Earl of Halifax]]\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date|1710|8|19|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = \n|death_date         = {{Death date and age|1763|08|21|1710|8|19|df=y}}\n|death_place        = \n|restingplace       = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|birthname          = \n|nationality        = \n|party              = \n|otherparty         =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse             = [[Alicia Wyndham, Countess of Egremont|Hon. Alicia Maria Carpenter]]\n|partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|children           = {{hlist|[[George O'Brien Wyndham, 3rd Earl of Egremont|George]]|[[Elizabeth Herbert, Countess of Carnarvon|Elizabeth]]|[[Frances Marsham, Lady Romney|Frances]]|[[Percy Charles Wyndham|Percy]]|[[Charles William Wyndham|Charles]]|[[William Frederick Wyndham|William]]}}\n|parents            = [[Sir William Wyndham, 3rd Baronet]]<br/>Catherine Seymour\n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = \n|occupation         = \n|profession         = \n|cabinet            = \n|committees         = \n|portfolio          = \n|religion           = \n|signature          = \n|signature_alt      = \n|website            = \n|footnotes          = \n}}\n[[File:WyndhamArmorials.PNG|thumb|Arms of Wyndham: ''Azure, a chevron between three lion's heads erased or'']]\n'''Charles Wyndham, 2nd Earl of Egremont''', [[Privy Council of Great Britain|PC]] (19 August 1710{{snd}}21 August 1763), of [[Orchard Wyndham]] in Somerset, [[Petworth House]] in Sussex, and of [[Cambridge House|Egremont House]] in [[Mayfair]], London, was a British [[Diplomat|statesman]] who served as [[Secretary of State for the Southern Department]] from 1761\u201363.\n\n==Origins==\nHe was the eldest son and heir of [[Sir William Wyndham, 3rd Baronet]] (c. 1688{{snd}}1740) of Orchard Wyndham, [[Secretary at War]] in 1712, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] in 1713 and [[Tory]] leader in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] during the reign of King [[George I of Great Britain|George I]] (1714\u20131727) and during the early years of King [[George II of Great Britain|George II]] (1727\u20131760). His mother was Catherine Seymour, daughter of [[Charles Seymour, 6th Duke of Somerset]] (1662\u20131748), [[Order of the Garter|KG]], and sister of [[Algernon Seymour, 7th Duke of Somerset]] (1684\u20131750), created in 1749 [[Earl of Egremont]] and [[Baron Cockermouth]], with special remainder to his nephew Charles Wyndham, subject of this article.<ref>Debretts peerage, 1968, p.411, Baron Leconfield and Egremont</ref>\n\n==Inheritance==\nHe succeeded to the Orchard Wyndham estates and as [[Wyndham baronets|4th baronet]] on his father's death in 1740 and in 1750 succeeded by [[special remainder]] as 2nd [[Earl of Egremont]],  on the death of his uncle [[Algernon Seymour, 7th Duke of Somerset|Algernon Seymour, 7th Duke of Somerset, 1st Earl of Egremont]], and received as his share of the Seymour inheritance the former Percy estates including [[Egremont Castle]] in Cumbria, [[Leconfield|Leconfield Castle]] in Yorkshire and the palatial [[Petworth House]] in [[Sussex]] (rebuilt by the 6th Duke<ref>\"In 1682 Petworth passed by marriage from the Percies to the 6th Duke of Somerset and it is to him ''the Proud Duke'' that we owe by far the larger part of the existing house\" ([[Nicolson, Nigel]], ''Great Houses of Britain'', London, 1978, p.165)</ref>). These were formerly owned by the [[House of Percy|Percy family]], and had been inherited by the 7th Duke of Somerset from his mother Lady [[Elizabeth Seymour, Duchess of Somerset|Elizabeth Percy]] (died 1722),<ref>Debrett's Peerage, 1968, p.411</ref> daughter and heiress  of [[Joceline Percy, 11th Earl of Northumberland]]. His younger brother was [[Percy Wyndham-O'Brien, 1st Earl of Thomond]], created [[Earl of Thomond]], having become the chosen heir of his mother's sister's childless husband [[Henry O'Brien, 8th Earl of Thomond]] (1688\u20131741).\n\n==Career==\nWyndham served as [[Member of Parliament]] for  [[Bridgwater (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridgwater]] (Somerset) in 1734\u20131741, [[Appleby (UK Parliament constituency)|Appleby]] (Cumberland) in 1741\u20131747, and for [[Taunton (UK Parliament constituency)|Taunton]] (Somerset) in 1747\u20131750.\n\n===Seven Years War===\n{{further|Great Britain in the Seven Years War}}\nIn October 1761 he was appointed [[Secretary of State for the Southern Department]] in succession to [[William Pitt, 1st Earl of Chatham]]. His term of office, during which he acted in concert with his brother-in-law [[George Grenville]], was mainly occupied with the declaration of war on Spain and with the negotiations for peace with France and Spain, the terms of which Wyndham seems to have disliked. He was also involved with the proceedings against [[John Wilkes]].<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Egremont, Earls of|volume=9|page=20}}</ref> He was [[Lord Lieutenant of Cumberland]] 1751-1763 and [[Lord Lieutenant of Sussex]] 1762\u20131763.\n\n==Marriage and progeny==\nOn 12 March 1750/51 Wyndham married [[Alicia Wyndham, Countess of Egremont|Hon. Alicia Maria Carpenter]], a daughter of [[George Carpenter, 2nd Baron Carpenter]] of Killaghy, by his wife Elizabeth Petty.<ref>[http://thepeerage.com/p1890.htm]</ref> He had progeny including:\n*[[George O'Brien Wyndham, 3rd Earl of Egremont]] (1751\u20131837).\n*[[Elizabeth Herbert, Countess of Carnarvon|Elizabeth Alicia Maria Wyndham]] (1752\u20131826), who married [[Henry Herbert, 1st Earl of Carnarvon]], and had children.\n*[[Frances Marsham, Lady Romney|Frances Wyndham]] (1755\u20131795), who married [[Charles Marsham, 1st Earl of Romney|Charles Marsham, later Earl of Romney]], and had children.\n*[[Percy Charles Wyndham]] (23 September 1757{{snd}}5 August 1833).\n*[[Charles William Wyndham]] (8 October 1760{{snd}}1 July 1828).\n*[[William Frederick Wyndham]] (1763\u20131828), who married Frances Mary Harford, daughter of [[Frederick Calvert, 6th Baron Baltimore]], and had children; his second wife was Julia de Smorzewska, Countess de Spyterki, by whom he also had children.\n\n==Death==\nHe died on 21 August 1763.\n\n==Assessment==\nAccording to the [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition|''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'' Eleventh Edition]], [[Horace Walpole]] perhaps rated Egremont's talents too low when he said he had neither knowledge of [[business]], nor the smallest share of parliamentary abilities.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bridgwater (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridgwater]]\n | years  = 1735&ndash;1741\n | with   = [[George Dodington, 1st Baron Melcombe|George Dodington]]\n | before = [[George Dodington, 1st Baron Melcombe|George Dodington]]<br />[[Thomas Palmer (died 1735)|Thomas Palmer]]\n | after  = [[George Dodington, 1st Baron Melcombe|George Dodington]]<br />[[Vere Poulett, 3rd Earl Poulett|Vere Poulett]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Appleby (UK Parliament constituency)|Appleby]]\n | years  = 1742&ndash;1747\n | with   = [[Sir John Ramsden, 3rd Baronet|Sir John Ramsden, Bt]]\n | before = [[Sir John Ramsden, 3rd Baronet|Sir John Ramsden, Bt]]<br />[[George Dodington, 1st Baron Melcombe|George Dodington]]\n | after  = [[Sir John Ramsden, 3rd Baronet|Sir John Ramsden, Bt]]<br />[[Randle Wilbraham]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Taunton (UK Parliament constituency)|Taunton]]\n | years  = 1747&ndash;1750\n | with   = [[Robert Webb (MP)|Robert Webb]]\n | before = [[Sir John Chapman, 2nd Baronet|Sir John Chapman, Bt]]<br />[[Percy Wyndham-O'Brien, 1st Earl of Thomond|Percy Wyndham-O'Brien]]\n | after  = [[Robert Webb (MP)|Robert Webb]]<br />[[William Rowley (Royal Navy officer)|William Rowley]]\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Secretary of State for the Southern Department]] | before=[[William Pitt, 1st Earl of Chatham|William Pitt]] | after=[[George Montague-Dunk, 2nd Earl of Halifax|The Earl of Halifax]] | years=1761\u20131763}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Leader of the House of Lords]]|before=[[Thomas Pelham-Holles, 1st Duke of Newcastle|The Duke of Newcastle]]|years=1762\u20131763|after=[[George Montague-Dunk, 2nd Earl of Halifax|The Earl of Halifax]]}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{s-bef | rows=2 | before=[[Henry Lowther, 3rd Viscount Lonsdale|The Viscount Lonsdale]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Lord Lieutenant of Cumberland]] | years=1751\u20131759}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[James Lowther, 1st Earl of Lonsdale|Sir James Lowther, 5th Bt]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Custos Rotulorum of Cumberland]] | years=1751\u20131763}}\n{{s-vac | rows=2 | next=[[James Lowther, 1st Earl of Lonsdale|Sir James Lowther, 5th Bt]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before=[[Sir James Lowther, 4th Baronet|Sir James Lowther, 4th Bt]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Vice-Admiral of Cumberland]] | years=1755\u20131763}}\n|-\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord Lieutenant of Sussex]] | before=[[Thomas Pelham-Holles, 1st Duke of Newcastle|The Duke of Newcastle]] | after=[[Charles Lennox, 3rd Duke of Richmond|The Duke of Richmond]] | years=1763}}\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Earl of Egremont]]\n  | years  = 1750&ndash;1763\n  | before = [[Algernon Seymour, 7th Duke of Somerset|Algernon Seymour]]\n  | after  = [[George Wyndham, 3rd Earl of Egremont|George Wyndham]]\n}}\n{{s-reg|en-bt}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Earl of Egremont|Baronet]]<br />'''(of Orchard Wyndham)'''\n  | years  = 1740&ndash;1763\n  | before = [[Sir William Wyndham, 3rd Baronet|William Wyndham]]\n  | after  = [[George Wyndham, 3rd Earl of Egremont|George Wyndham]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{College of William & Mary chancellors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Egremont, Charles Wyndham, 2nd Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1710 births]]\n[[Category:1763 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the College of William & Mary|Wyndham, Charles]]\n[[Category:Earls in the Peerage of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Lord-Lieutenants of Cumberland]]\n[[Category:Lord-Lieutenants of Sussex]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies|Wyndham, Charles]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1734\u20131741]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1741\u20131747]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1747\u20131754]]\n[[Category:Wyndham family|Charles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Charles Wyndham}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name               = The Earl of Egremont\n|honorific-suffix   = [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]]\n|image              = Charles Wyndham, 2nd Earl of Egremont by William Hoare lowres color.jpg\n|imagesize          = 240px\n|alt                = \n|caption            = \n|order              = \n|office             = [[Secretary of State for the Southern Department]]\n|term_start         =  9 October 1761\n|term_end           = 21 August 1763\n|monarch            = [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]]\n|primeminister      = [[John Stuart, 3rd Earl of Bute|The Earl of Bute]]<br/>[[George Grenville]]\n|predecessor        = [[William Pitt, 1st Earl of Chatham|William Pitt]]\n|successor          = [[George Montagu-Dunk, 2nd Earl of Halifax|The Earl of Halifax]]\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date|1710|8|19|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = \n|death_date         = {{Death date and age|1763|08|21|1710|8|19|df=y}}\n|death_place        = \n|restingplace       = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|birthname          = \n|nationality        = \n|party              = \n|otherparty         =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse             = [[Alicia Wyndham, Countess of Egremont|Hon. Alicia Maria Carpenter]]\n|partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|children           = {{hlist|[[George O'Brien Wyndham, 3rd Earl of Egremont|George]]|[[Elizabeth Herbert, Countess of Carnarvon|Elizabeth]]|[[Frances Marsham, Lady Romney|Frances]]|[[Percy Charles Wyndham|Percy]]|[[Charles William Wyndham|Charles]]|[[William Frederick Wyndham|William]]}}\n|parents            = [[Sir William Wyndham, 3rd Baronet]]<br/>Catherine Seymour\n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = \n|occupation         = \n|profession         = \n|cabinet            = \n|committees         = \n|portfolio          = \n|religion           = \n|signature          = \n|signature_alt      = \n|website            = \n|footnotes          = \n}}\n[[File:WyndhamArmorials.PNG|thumb|Arms of Wyndham: ''Azure, a chevron between three lion's heads erased or'']]\n'''Charles Wyndham, 2nd Earl of Egremont''', [[Privy Council of Great Britain|PC]] (19 August 1710{{snd}}21 August 1763), of [[Orchard Wyndham]] in Somerset, [[Petworth House]] in Sussex, and of [[Cambridge House|Egremont House]] in [[Mayfair]], London, was a British [[Diplomat|statesman]] who served as [[Secretary of State for the Southern Department]] from 1761-63.\n\n==Origins==\nHe was the eldest son and heir of [[Sir William Wyndham, 3rd Baronet]] (c. 1688{{snd}}1740) of Orchard Wyndham, [[Secretary at War]] in 1712, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] in 1713 and [[Tory]] leader in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] during the reign of King [[George I of Great Britain|George I]] (1714\u20131727) and during the early years of King [[George II of Great Britain|George II]] (1727\u20131760). His mother was Catherine Seymour, daughter of [[Charles Seymour, 6th Duke of Somerset]] (1662\u20131748), [[Order of the Garter|KG]], and sister of [[Algernon Seymour, 7th Duke of Somerset]] (1684\u20131750), created in 1749 [[Earl of Egremont]] and [[Baron Cockermouth]], with special remainder to his nephew Charles Wyndham, subject of this article.<ref>Debretts peerage, 1968, p.411, Baron Leconfield and Egremont</ref>\n\n==Inheritance==\nHe succeeded to the Orchard Wyndham estates and as [[Wyndham baronets|4th baronet]] on his father's death in 1740 and in 1750 succeeded by [[special remainder]] as 2nd [[Earl of Egremont]],  on the death of his uncle [[Algernon Seymour, 7th Duke of Somerset|Algernon Seymour, 7th Duke of Somerset, 1st Earl of Egremont]], and received as his share of the Seymour inheritance the former Percy estates including [[Egremont Castle]] in Cumbria, [[Leconfield|Leconfield Castle]] in Yorkshire and the palatial [[Petworth House]] in [[Sussex]] (rebuilt by the 6th Duke<ref>\"In 1682 Petworth passed by marriage from the Percies to the 6th Duke of Somerset and it is to him ''the Proud Duke'' that we owe by far the larger part of the existing house\" ([[Nicolson, Nigel]], ''Great Houses of Britain'', London, 1978, p.165)</ref>). These were formerly owned by the [[House of Percy|Percy family]], and had been inherited by the 7th Duke of Somerset from his mother Lady [[Elizabeth Seymour, Duchess of Somerset|Elizabeth Percy]] (died 1722),<ref>Debrett's Peerage, 1968, p.411</ref> daughter and heiress  of [[Joceline Percy, 11th Earl of Northumberland]]. His younger brother was [[Percy Wyndham-O'Brien, 1st Earl of Thomond]], created [[Earl of Thomond]], having become the chosen heir of his mother's sister's childless husband [[Henry O'Brien, 8th Earl of Thomond]] (1688\u20131741).\n\n==Career==\nWyndham served as [[Member of Parliament]] for  [[Bridgwater (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridgwater]] (Somerset) in 1734\u20131741, [[Appleby (UK Parliament constituency)|Appleby]] (Cumberland) in 1741\u20131747, and for [[Taunton (UK Parliament constituency)|Taunton]] (Somerset) in 1747\u20131750.\n\n===Seven Years War===\n{{further|Great Britain in the Seven Years War}}\nIn October 1761 he was appointed [[Secretary of State for the Southern Department]] in succession to [[William Pitt, 1st Earl of Chatham]]. His term of office, during which he acted in concert with his brother-in-law [[George Grenville]], was mainly occupied with the declaration of war on Spain and with the negotiations for peace with France and Spain, the terms of which Wyndham seems to have disliked. He was also involved with the proceedings against [[John Wilkes]].<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Egremont, Earls of|volume=9|page=20}}</ref> He was [[Lord Lieutenant of Cumberland]] 1751-1763 and [[Lord Lieutenant of Sussex]] 1762-1763.\n\n==Marriage and progeny==\nOn 12 March 1750/51 Wyndham married [[Alicia Wyndham, Countess of Egremont|Hon. Alicia Maria Carpenter]], a daughter of [[George Carpenter, 2nd Baron Carpenter]] of Killaghy, by his wife Elizabeth Petty.<ref>[http://thepeerage.com/p1890.htm]</ref> He had progeny including:\n*[[George O'Brien Wyndham, 3rd Earl of Egremont]] (1751\u20131837).\n*[[Elizabeth Herbert, Countess of Carnarvon|Elizabeth Alicia Maria Wyndham]] (1752\u20131826), who married [[Henry Herbert, 1st Earl of Carnarvon]], and had children.\n*[[Frances Marsham, Lady Romney|Frances Wyndham]] (1755\u20131795), who married [[Charles Marsham, 1st Earl of Romney|Charles Marsham, later Earl of Romney]], and had children.\n*[[Percy Charles Wyndham]] (23 September 1757{{snd}}5 August 1833).\n*[[Charles William Wyndham]] (8 October 1760{{snd}}1 July 1828).\n*[[William Frederick Wyndham]] (1763\u20131828), who married Frances Mary Harford, daughter of [[Frederick Calvert, 6th Baron Baltimore]], and had children; his second wife was Julia de Smorzewska, Countess de Spyterki, by whom he also had children.\n\n==Death==\nHe died on 21 August 1763.\n\n==Assessment==\nAccording to the [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition|''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'' Eleventh Edition]], [[Horace Walpole]] perhaps rated Egremont's talents too low when he said he had neither knowledge of [[business]], nor the smallest share of parliamentary abilities.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bridgwater (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridgwater]]\n | years  = 1735&ndash;1741\n | with   = [[George Dodington, 1st Baron Melcombe|George Dodington]]\n | before = [[George Dodington, 1st Baron Melcombe|George Dodington]]<br />[[Thomas Palmer (died 1735)|Thomas Palmer]]\n | after  = [[George Dodington, 1st Baron Melcombe|George Dodington]]<br />[[Vere Poulett, 3rd Earl Poulett|Vere Poulett]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Appleby (UK Parliament constituency)|Appleby]]\n | years  = 1742&ndash;1747\n | with   = [[Sir John Ramsden, 3rd Baronet|Sir John Ramsden, Bt]]\n | before = [[Sir John Ramsden, 3rd Baronet|Sir John Ramsden, Bt]]<br />[[George Dodington, 1st Baron Melcombe|George Dodington]]\n | after  = [[Sir John Ramsden, 3rd Baronet|Sir John Ramsden, Bt]]<br />[[Randle Wilbraham]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [